In an interview this weekend I said something like ‚ÄúYou don‚Äôt rise to the level of your goals, you fall to the level of your preparation‚Äù , which is pretty close to a quote from the book Atomic Habits. 
Anyway... before @dxbfitnesschamp started I was asked what my plans and goals were? Did I want to win, podium, finish top10, secure my Games invite, win an event.?.. etc. All that stuff obviously crosses everyone‚Äôs mind before an event, and I think everyone wants all those things. Wanting them doesn‚Äôt separate anyone though. What separates everyone is how fit you happen to be relative to the tests, your execution, a bit of luck, and all the little things you do that others don‚Äôt in your prep. And the nice thing is I had all those pieces fall into place this week here in Dubai. I‚Äôm grateful, I‚Äôm quite frankly pretty stoked. I‚Äôve competed for a long time, and I‚Äôve done all those things in prep for a lot of other competitions and it doesn‚Äôt always work out this well. So what‚Äôs the punch line of this winding caption? Another good question. Maybe it‚Äôs keep trying. Maybe it‚Äôs enjoy the process because victory is never guaranteed. Maybe it‚Äôs just a good opportunity to admire a nice photo taken by @fitness.shots where you can appreciate that the orange shorts I brought from home matched the lettering on the jersey perfectly üëå #reebokathlete
Ok that‚Äôs it. Keep scrolling pal.
